comment:
If my husband lost almost all of his money, firstly, I would try to be as supportive as possible but, if I said ‚Äúboo‚Äù which causes him to punch me in the face, I don‚Äôt think I‚Äôd even be mad at him right away. I would just get the hell out of his way! 

(before reading further, let me preface this by saying I am not talking about actual physical or mental abuse below. That is something else entirely. I am talking about stressful situations that make you act not quite like yourself but not a violently dangerous person) 

I just feel that a lot of times, when we are going through very stressful situations that causes our emotions to be all over the place, sometimes we take out our frustration on the person we love the most. We do this because, when you truly love someone, and you are their partner, you don‚Äôt fear being judged or abandoned. You know that person is going to stay with you through the good and bad. For example, when my husband‚Äòs father died, I was beside him 24/7. He wasn‚Äôt always the nicest when he was going through his grief. He said horrible things to me, got drunk and broke shit. But, he knows that I‚Äôm not going to think of that as abuse and leave him. We all get upset & we all do stupid shit. And let‚Äôs not forget Johnny was having a hard time dealing with his mothers passing at the same time as dealing with this mess.  If someone Who is supposed to love you & support you is trying to videotape you when you‚Äôre at your most vulnerable, that‚Äôs not love, that is something else entirely. That is spiteful, vindictive, hateful bitterness

comment:
Its not uncommon for DV victims to film  or try to film assults. Police officers recommend this as without video footage its really hard to get evidence. 

On another note, victims do sometimes bait if they've know they've been hurt and need to capture it. Its a desperation act and it's not a result of a personality disorder or narcissism. I dont know what amber heard is, but there needs to be an adjustment there. Victims can bait, its not malicious its out of desperation if they can't get away or find a need for revenge to prove theyve been hurt. Is it okay - no. But its not as clear cut as people think. Some people freak out, go numb, they may faint or go into themselves.It depends on what their nervous system is trained for. Its super weird timing, but depending on how their trauma cycle is bonded. It's just not clear from this footage either. There's not enough context. The real abuser might be intimidating, they may do what amber heard did and manipulate, or they might be on the other end. in the end it does matter for restorative justice but what matters after is them both getting the hell out and getting help. If they both can't see they need help after this then that is very revealing too. This footage would be need to be viewed in context of the years together which is why the courts are struggling. If it was a simple as looking at this footage it wouldn't be taking the courts this long. It's not a clear cut answer.

comment: This is an abusive relationship.  This is not a relationship of mutual fault.  It is a relationship of dominance and control and the one exerting that is Amber.  Abusers thrive in conflict.  They set the victim up to create a fight, then sit back and blame the victim for the fight.  The purpose of the fights are to portray the victim to him/herself in the worst light possible.  We've heard the fight audios where Amber dumps all the blame on Johnny even when Johnny is avoiding any conflict/violence with her and she makes the relationship problem about Johnny leaving when she gets violent.  This isn't a relationship of mutuality, or a toxic relationship in which both parties contribute to the problem.  Johnny detoxed from drugs and alcohol early in the relationship and Amber continued to bring drugs and alcohol into the house.  The staff testified to the fact that Amber was a heavy consumer of alcohol and Amber herself in the Australia audio talks about the range of drugs she consumed.  If Amber were REALLY concerned about Johnny's drug and alcohol problem, she would have gone alcohol and drug free, kept them out of the house, and yet she didn't.  In one audio, we hear her giving Johnny a xanax to dull him down when she can't win the fight.  So she used drugs and alcohol as tool against him to get him to accept her crazy behavior.   This relationship is not about Johnny's drug use or Johnny's poor coping skills.  We hear in the audios that he is calm, he hear him trying to rationalize with her, we hear her screaming at him and making unreasonable attacks and demands.   Yes the relationship is toxic in general but both parties don't bring the toxicity to this relationship.  Assigning blame to Johnny is victim blaming.  The fault lies at the feet of Amber who is the puppeteer.  I am a survivor of DV so I've gone through what Johnny has gone through.  If you are not well versed in DV, you jump to conclusions that these are relationships of mutuality.  You can see in this video, Amber setting Johnny up and getting off on getting one over on him.
